          <h3>Schlage Encode Plus: Best Overall</h3>
          <p>The Schlage Encode Plus is the gold standard for Airbnb property managers. Built-in WiFi means no hub or bridge is required, and it connects directly to your router for remote access. Schlage's reputation for commercial-grade security carries over here: the lock is BHMA Grade 1 certified, the highest residential security rating available.</p>

          <p>What makes it stand out for short-term rentals is its rock-solid PMS integration. It works seamlessly with all major property management software platforms, allowing automatic code generation and expiry tied to booking windows. Apple Home Key support (tap your iPhone to unlock) is a premium feature guests love. The price of $250-300 is at the top end, but the reliability justifies it for serious hosts.</p>

          <h3>Yale Assure Lock 2: Best Design</h3>
          <p>Yale's Assure Lock 2 brings a clean, minimalist look that fits modern condo interiors far better than most competing locks. The WiFi module (purchased separately or in a bundle) enables the same remote management and PMS integration as the Schlage. It operates within the August app ecosystem, which has an excellent reputation for stability and feature updates.</p>

          <p>At $200-280, it sits in the mid-to-high range but offers a strong combination of aesthetics, reliability, and integration depth. The Yale name is trusted by building management, which can help when seeking condo board approval.</p>

          <h3>August WiFi Smart Lock: Best for Condos</h3>
          <p>The August WiFi Smart Lock is a retrofit solution, meaning it replaces only the interior thumb-turn of your existing deadbolt. The exterior of the door remains unchanged, which is critical for Toronto condo hosts whose buildings prohibit exterior door modifications. See the <a href="/blog/can-i-airbnb-my-condo-toronto-2026">condo Airbnb guide</a> for more on board restrictions.</p>

          <p>Installation takes about 15 minutes with no special tools. The built-in WiFi enables full remote management and PMS integration, and the auto-lock feature ensures the door is never accidentally left unlocked. At $200-250, it's competitively priced given its retrofit capability. The one trade-off: the interior unit is larger and more visible than a full deadbolt replacement.</p>

          <h3>igloohome Smart Deadbolt: Best for Remote Properties</h3>
          <p>igloohome's standout feature is its offline PIN technology. Codes are cryptographically generated in the cloud and synced to the lock via Bluetooth, but once set, they work without any WiFi or Bluetooth connection at the door. This is transformative for cottage hosts or rural properties where internet reliability is inconsistent.</p>

          <p>Despite the offline-first design, igloohome integrates with most PMS platforms via cloud sync. Codes are generated automatically per booking and programmed to expire at checkout. Battery life is exceptional: 12-18 months on standard AA batteries because the lock draws no power for WiFi. At $150-200, it is excellent value for the specific use case it solves.</p>

          <h3>Kwikset Halo: Solid Mid-Range</h3>
          <p>The Kwikset Halo offers built-in WiFi and PMS compatibility at a mid-range price of $150-200. Kwikset's SmartKey re-key technology allows you to change the physical key without a locksmith. It lacks the premium feel of Schlage or Yale but performs reliably for everyday hosting. A practical choice for hosts who want WiFi capability without the premium price tag.</p>

