          <h2 id="condo-considerations">Condo Considerations for Toronto Hosts</h2>
          <p>Toronto hosts face a challenge that freehold property owners don't: many condo corporations prohibit modifications to suite entrance doors. This restriction exists because the door and its hardware are technically common element property, not the unit owner's property to modify freely.</p>

          <p>Before purchasing any smart lock, take these steps:</p>

          <ul>
            <li><strong>Review your condo declaration:</strong> Look for language about "entrance doors," "common elements," or "alterations." If modifications require board approval, start that process early.</li>
            <li><strong>Contact your property management office:</strong> Ask specifically whether replacing the interior thumb-turn only (retrofit) is permitted. Many buildings that prohibit exterior changes allow interior-only retrofits.</li>
            <li><strong>Get written approval:</strong> Verbal approval is not enough. Get any permission in writing before purchasing a lock. This protects you if management personnel changes.</li>
            <li><strong>Consider the August as your first choice:</strong> Because it leaves the exterior keyway, strike plate, and face of the deadbolt unchanged, it is the most likely to meet condo building standards. The exterior of the door looks identical before and after installation.</li>
          </ul>

          <p>For more detail on what your condo corporation can and cannot restrict for short-term rentals, see the full guide on <a href="/blog/can-i-airbnb-my-condo-toronto-2026">Airbnb in Toronto condos</a>.</p>

          <h3>Buildings with Fob Entry Systems</h3>
          <p>Some newer Toronto condo buildings use key fob access for suite doors rather than traditional deadbolts. These systems are typically managed by the building and cannot be replaced with third-party smart locks. In this case, a lockbox at a secure location inside the building (if permitted) or lobby-level key exchange via a concierge is the alternative. Contact your building management to understand your specific options.</p>

          <h2 id="backup-access">Backup Access Plans</h2>
          <p>Even the most reliable smart lock can fail. Dead batteries, WiFi outages, a guest who accidentally deletes the code email, or a rare firmware glitch can all strand a guest outside your property. A backup plan is not optional; it's part of operating a professional listing.</p>

